{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17509925","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17509925"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:21:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:21:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11465"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11465","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11465"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.73,0.03,0.02,0.2,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4097"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56278"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4097","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4097"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11465"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41833"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"191"},{"type":"tags","id":"1284"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4841"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4963"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5258"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10884"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16016"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16072"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42606"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56278","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/56278"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 40-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic for a review. Three months ago, he was assessed for management of his obesity. At that time, his BMI was 35 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003Eand his weight was beginning to impact his health, with a raised blood pressure of 135/82 mmHg. Apart from lifestyle measures, he was started on pharmacological therapy to help him lose weight. He has no significant medical history and takes no other regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn review, he has managed to lose weight (BMI 30 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E) and his blood pressure is 126/80 mmHg.  He is happy with his progress and still has a good appetite, but reports flatulence and foul-smelling stools that are difficult to flush.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following drugs is the most likely cause of his current presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Orlistat","Phentermine","Naltrexone-bupropion","Liraglutide","Topiramate"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient\u0027s symptoms of flatulence and foul-smelling, difficult-to-flush stools are highly suggestive of steatorrhoea, which is the most common side effect of \u003Cstrong\u003Eorlistat\u003C/strong\u003E. Orlistat is a pancreatic lipase inhibitor that causes incomplete fat hydrolysis and increased faecal fat excretion. It is considered the first-line pharmacotherapy for obesity management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPhentermine\u003C/strong\u003E is a sympathomimetic agent that suppresses appetite. Its side effects are generally mild and include dry mouth, insomnia, agitation, constipation, and tachycardia. It does not cause steatorrhoea.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENaltrexone-bupropion\u003C/strong\u003E is a combination therapy used as an adjunct to diet and exercise for weight management. Its common side effects include nausea, constipation, vomiting, and dizziness, but not steatorrhoea.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELiraglutide\u003C/strong\u003E is a glucagon-like peptide-1 (GLP-1) agonist used in the treatment of type 2 diabetes and obesity. Its common side effects include nausea, vomiting, diarrhoea, constipation, and dyspepsia, but not steatorrhoea.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopiramate\u003C/strong\u003E is an anticonvulsant sometimes used off-label for weight loss. Its side effects are dose-dependent and commonly include paraesthesia, dry mouth, constipation, altered taste sensation, insomnia, and dizziness, but not steatorrhoea.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, among the options provided, only orlistat is associated with steatorrhoea as a common side effect. This makes it the most likely cause of the patient\u0027s current presentation, given his history of recent pharmacological treatment for obesity and the characteristic symptoms he is experiencing.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Steatorrhoea is the most common side effect of orlistat due to its mechanism of action"],"references":["Filippatos TD, Derdemezis CS, Gazi IF, Nakou ES, Mikhailidis DP, Elisaf MS. Orlistat-associated adverse effects and drug interactions: a critical review. Drug Saf. 2008;31(1):53-65. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/18095746/","Pi-Sunyer X, Astrup A, Fujioka K, Greenway F, Halpern A, Krempf M, Lau DC, Le Roux CW, Violante Ortiz R, Jensen CB, Wilding JP. A randomized, controlled trial of 3.0 mg of liraglutide in weight management. New England Journal of Medicine. 2015 Jul 2;373(1):11-22. Available at: https://www.nejm.org/doi/full/10.1056/NEJMoa1411892","Lee PC, Dixon J. Pharmacotherapy for obesity. Australian family physician. 2017 Jul;46(7):472-7. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2017/july/pharmacotherapy-for-obesity"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41833"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11465"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41833","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/41833"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-19T22:14:42+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-19T22:15:15+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4097"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56278"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","pos